Written near misses' reports are generated and discussed with appropriate personnel. The incident investigation team prepares a written summary at the conclusion of the investigation that includes at a minimum: five



?    Description of the incident including Date and Time;

?    Date and Time the investigation was initiated;

?    Team members and expertise;

?    Factors that contributed to the incident or near miss and;

?    Recommendations formulated as a result of the investigation.



E.     The Emergency Response Program



Brandt has a Consolidated Emergency Response/Contingency Plan that has been included under the California Environmental Reporting System (CERS). The plan lists emergency containment and cleanup procedures, emergency equipment on-site and a list of the telephone numbers of to contact in the event of an emergency. Internal response will occur and evacuation maps are posted on-site. Neighboring facilities that may be affected by an off-site release will be contacted via telephone. The most recent review or update of the emergency response plan will be conducted on Approx. March 15, 2018. Employee training on the Plan that will take place on March 15, 2018. The primary local emergency response agency with which the Plan is coordinated is Tulare County Environmental Services (EHS) as well as the Tulare County Fire Department. There is no known other federal or state emergency plan requirements to which the stationary source is subject.



